1
00:00:00,750 --> 00:00:02,210
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:03,170 --> 00:00:10,210
Today we'll look at a pretty well-known and interesting circuit called a Kacher.

3
00:00:12,370 --> 00:00:26,890
This circuit is a self-oscillator built on a single transistor with feedback running directly from the cold end of the high-voltage coil to that transistor's base.

4
00:00:27,530 --> 00:00:29,250
Why do we need this circuit?

5
00:00:29,910 --> 00:00:41,110
This circuit will help us answer the question of what frequency to tune the Tesla coil to, relative to our resonator in the grenade.

6
00:00:43,130 --> 00:00:45,930
This is a question subscribers ask often.

7
00:00:47,170 --> 00:00:51,250
So we'll build this circuit on this transistor.

8
00:00:51,330 --> 00:00:52,830
I think everyone has one.

9
00:00:53,870 --> 00:00:54,490
2SC5200.

10
00:00:56,550 --> 00:01:01,450
We're going with it because it's widely available and easy to buy.

11
00:01:02,870 --> 00:01:06,330
And we'll look at how this system runs.

12
00:01:06,750 --> 00:01:12,670
What we know and what we still don't know about tuning these systems.

13
00:01:13,590 --> 00:01:14,910
Walking through our circuit.

14
00:01:15,450 --> 00:01:20,490
At the power input we have a plus-minus DC supply.

15
00:01:21,810 --> 00:01:27,410
Power hits the first filter capacitor right away.

16
00:01:29,490 --> 00:01:33,110
That cap is 100 nF, 275 V.

17
00:01:33,470 --> 00:01:37,950
Next it hits a common-mode line filter.

18
00:01:38,650 --> 00:01:44,970
It's specifically designed so that DC passes straight through the filter capacitance.

19
00:01:44,970 --> 00:01:49,890
Unimpeded — any AC component gets suppressed.

20
00:01:50,510 --> 00:01:55,950
After that, the output hits another filter cap.

21
00:01:56,350 --> 00:01:58,870
Also 100 nF, 275 V.

22
00:02:00,110 --> 00:02:05,970
And then the power hits the main reservoir cap.

23
00:02:06,310 --> 00:02:07,910
An electrolytic capacitor.

24
00:02:08,670 --> 00:02:11,510
Its capacitance is 47 µF at 400 V.

25
00:02:12,050 --> 00:02:27,410
The voltage rating on this cap should be no less than 400 V, because high-voltage potential can show up in the system, so the cap doesn't blow or get punctured by a high-voltage pickup.

26
00:02:27,410 --> 00:02:29,590
From a high-voltage pickup.

27
00:02:30,650 --> 00:02:37,990
Then in parallel with it, a capacitor is installed that also has special requirements.

28
00:02:38,370 --> 00:02:40,150
Also no less than 400 V.

29
00:02:41,250 --> 00:02:44,090
Capacitance in this case is 155 nF.

30
00:02:45,970 --> 00:02:47,990
The requirements are these.

31
00:02:48,170 --> 00:02:52,290
Has to be a film cap, high-frequency rated.

32
00:02:52,370 --> 00:02:55,450
CBB81 type works.

33
00:02:56,770 --> 00:03:07,670
It's needed to form a sharp pulse that'll show up on the transistor's collector.

34
00:03:09,090 --> 00:03:15,090
That pulse then goes to the inductor of the Tesla high-voltage coil.

35
00:03:17,050 --> 00:03:29,530
The system is built on the transistor plus two resistors that form a voltage divider.

36
00:03:30,470 --> 00:03:40,870
One resistor connects directly between minus supply and the transistor base, the other between plus supply and the base.

37
00:03:41,390 --> 00:03:49,090
A voltage divider is formed that creates a bias point on the transistor's base.

38
00:03:49,850 --> 00:04:04,450
But what you can't forget here is that it's not only the two resistors at work — there's also the resistance formed by the base-emitter junction inside the transistor's semiconductor.

39
00:04:05,670 --> 00:04:09,410
So we get a more complex divider to minus.

40
00:04:09,630 --> 00:04:12,250
Three resistances in play.

41
00:04:13,070 --> 00:04:19,670
In this case, the base-emitter resistor is 2.7 kΩ.

42
00:04:20,010 --> 00:04:26,710
The resistor between plus supply and base is 3.3 kΩ.

43
00:04:27,430 --> 00:04:32,350
Tested values from 1 to 10 kΩ — works.

44
00:04:34,350 --> 00:04:44,430
The higher the value of this resistor, the less the whole system consumes overall.

45
00:04:45,030 --> 00:04:47,470
Interesting behavior.

46
00:04:48,250 --> 00:04:51,970
We'll examine that later, just laying out the basics for now.

47
00:04:52,570 --> 00:04:57,570
On the oscilloscope, we should see this signal.

48
00:04:58,530 --> 00:05:08,530
The width of this signal corresponds to half a period of the high-voltage coil's oscillation.

49
00:05:09,310 --> 00:05:15,630
And inside that signal, we want as many high-frequency peaks as possible.

50
00:05:16,430 --> 00:05:29,070
They essentially drop down to the supply rail in voltage scale width.

51
00:05:29,990 --> 00:05:33,670
But not quite all the way down.

52
00:05:33,870 --> 00:05:44,190
And what we end up with is the system getting kicked with high-voltage, high-frequency pulses.

53
00:05:44,310 --> 00:05:49,870
But overall, the high-voltage coil sees it as a single pulse.

54
00:05:51,210 --> 00:05:56,110
And the more peaks, the better the system ramps up.

55
00:05:58,230 --> 00:06:15,790
Also, if this system is used directly on the setup, here's one way to synchronize it simply — here's a schematic of our pot core, the deflection unit from a TV screen.

56
00:06:15,790 --> 00:06:16,470
TV screen.

57
00:06:17,830 --> 00:06:28,410
28 turns, however many fit on half — we put it on this output, or a fast-acting diode.

58
00:06:29,710 --> 00:06:43,590
This way we chop off the half from the signal, pass a half-period of it, and feed it to the power input.

59
00:06:44,550 --> 00:06:49,830
This cap right here will block the high-voltage spike.

60
00:06:51,270 --> 00:06:59,770
As a high-voltage signal, it might be anywhere from 100 to 350–400 volts.

61
00:06:59,870 --> 00:07:03,350
That is, when the system absorbs it, it doesn't go higher.

62
00:07:03,350 --> 00:07:06,290
There's also some drop across the diode.

63
00:07:07,590 --> 00:07:15,510
And what this filter is mainly for — it removes all the noise.

64
00:07:16,130 --> 00:07:25,830
The power that reaches the system is already single-polarity, synchronized with one half-period of the push-pull.

65
00:07:26,350 --> 00:07:38,890
When it's running, we just need to switch the diode either here or here, or swap these wires, and we can run the system on the positive half-period or, say, the negative one.

66
00:07:38,890 --> 00:07:39,610
Negative.

67
00:07:39,710 --> 00:07:41,290
The simplest synchronization.

68
00:07:41,870 --> 00:07:43,470
Not the most efficient, of course.

69
00:07:44,130 --> 00:07:52,030
Electronic synchronization is much more effective, but this kind of sync is workable too.

70
00:07:54,930 --> 00:08:08,290
Using this filter — two capacitors and a counter-wound transformer on a single core — provides some isolation from the power source.

71
00:08:08,530 --> 00:08:18,910
And most importantly, if we're using this sync system, it removes any interference present at the input.

72
00:08:19,630 --> 00:08:32,270
It also filters interference that might travel back from the Tesla high-voltage coil's operation toward the power source.

73
00:08:32,870 --> 00:08:37,750
You'll also see we have grounding.

74
00:08:38,050 --> 00:08:42,030
It connects directly to the emitter of this transistor.

75
00:08:44,970 --> 00:08:51,550
And if you look, the minus runs through the filter to grounding.

76
00:08:52,230 --> 00:08:56,610
Our grounding isn't directly connected either.

77
00:08:56,830 --> 00:09:05,230
There's a galvanic connection, but there's no connection for the high-frequency side.

78
00:09:05,350 --> 00:09:15,430
That's how we protect the rest of the system from interference that may show up during the coil's operation.

79
00:09:16,890 --> 00:09:18,690
Here's another interesting point.

80
00:09:19,250 --> 00:09:24,750
This transistor has pretty solid specs.

81
00:09:25,270 --> 00:09:33,330
Collector-base voltage maxes out at 230 V.

82
00:09:33,830 --> 00:09:38,090
Collector-emitter voltage is also 230 V max.

83
00:09:38,590 --> 00:09:45,950
And emitter-base voltage is only 5 V of absolute maximum control.

84
00:09:47,110 --> 00:09:54,970
How does it work, hooking our transistor directly to the cold end of the high-voltage coil?

85
00:09:55,150 --> 00:09:57,530
There are seemingly kilovolts there.

86
00:09:58,250 --> 00:10:03,330
Why does this transistor work with a max of 5 V?

87
00:10:04,230 --> 00:10:13,990
The thing is, during operation of the Tesla high-voltage coil, we have a phase shift between current and voltage.

88
00:10:14,570 --> 00:10:22,130
And at the base-emitter junction, there's no high voltage as such.

89
00:10:23,410 --> 00:10:38,190
Depending on the mode, it might be tenths of a volt, or, depending on the bias point and coil ramp-up, up to 2–2.5 volts.

90
00:10:38,330 --> 00:10:50,070
And to understand this — so our transistor doesn't blow up — we created a bias with the resistor divider, a positive potential.

91
00:10:50,430 --> 00:11:02,270
And our transistor opens because it's NPN-type — the conductivity of this transistor is triggered by the positive half-period.

92
00:11:02,370 --> 00:11:15,590
And we need to watch that at that point, the bias voltage on the base plus the voltage potential present during the positive half-period don't exceed 5 V.

93
00:11:16,250 --> 00:11:19,570
Past that, the transistor blows.

94
00:11:21,370 --> 00:11:38,170
It works up to +150°C, and we need to understand that this 150°C is the temperature at the semiconductor crystal itself.

95
00:11:38,570 --> 00:11:53,490
If we look at the transistor, the semiconductor die is in this zone, mounted on a metal pad that serves both as a heat-removal pad and is galvanically connected directly to the collector.

96
00:11:53,490 --> 00:11:58,650
To the collector of the transistor.

97
00:11:59,530 --> 00:12:07,350
So in this case, 150°C is the die temperature, not the heat sink temperature.

98
00:12:07,970 --> 00:12:23,370
You need to watch the heat sink temperature for this transistor — if it rises to 120°C, there's a danger of the transistor blowing, because the die itself at 120°C of heat sink will already be around 145°C inside.

99
00:12:23,370 --> 00:12:32,630
Inside the transistor.

100
00:12:33,130 --> 00:12:41,910
But this circuit is designed so we won't see big temperature rises here.

101
00:12:42,110 --> 00:12:51,670
At 24 V supply — I tested it up to 50 V too — the heat sink handles it easily, basically no heating.

102
00:12:52,310 --> 00:13:07,610
In some videos we saw the system tuned so there's a single pulse to maximize the output amplitude.

103
00:13:08,110 --> 00:13:15,290
From practice, this turned out not to be the operating mode we want.

104
00:13:15,890 --> 00:13:33,330
Maximum coil output at minimum consumption can only happen when the transistor operates in this high-frequency pulsed mode relative to the coil's own frequency.

105
00:13:34,450 --> 00:13:40,630
Now let's look at how the system is implemented in metal.

106
00:13:42,210 --> 00:13:50,910
Here's the circuit layout where all the parts are mounted.

107
00:13:52,350 --> 00:13:54,930
What do we see first?

108
00:13:55,610 --> 00:13:59,310
Power input terminals — plus and minus.

109
00:14:00,350 --> 00:14:16,250
First, the filter cap at 100 nF, then the filter itself with counter windings, then the second cap, the main reservoir, and the main fast-discharge cap.

110
00:14:17,030 --> 00:14:20,390
From it goes the plus output — minus is here.

111
00:14:20,810 --> 00:14:25,470
A wire from minus goes straight to grounding.

112
00:14:26,790 --> 00:14:36,270
The divider system that creates the bias on the transistor's base is set up for adjustment.

113
00:14:37,870 --> 00:14:45,390
One resistor goes to plus, the other connects to minus — directly to the emitter.

114
00:14:45,450 --> 00:14:46,870
This wire goes to the base.

115
00:14:47,410 --> 00:14:54,190
The divider is picked for optimal operation, then mounted on the board.

116
00:14:55,070 --> 00:15:00,590
The transistor sits on a massive heat sink.

117
00:15:00,770 --> 00:15:03,970
As it turned out, you don't need a heat sink this big.

118
00:15:04,510 --> 00:15:12,690
With this system, at 24 V supply, the heat sink doesn't go above 45°C.

119
00:15:12,850 --> 00:15:14,410
You can use a smaller heat sink.

120
00:15:15,010 --> 00:15:36,310
I didn't use a thermal-insulating pad — the one that galvanically isolates the heat sink from the transistor — to get better cooling for the system.

121
00:15:37,550 --> 00:15:42,250
So the heat sink is the collector of this transistor.

122
00:15:42,430 --> 00:15:46,870
You can probe the oscilloscope directly off it.

123
00:15:48,730 --> 00:15:54,570
Moving on to what I'd say is the most important part of our system.

124
00:15:55,050 --> 00:15:57,710
This is our high-voltage coil.

125
00:16:00,110 --> 00:16:11,650
In a lot of videos online, you see these coils wound on tubes taken from sewer pipe — that is, plastic.

126
00:16:12,510 --> 00:16:19,390
As it turned out in practice, plastic is not at all suitable for winding these coils.

127
00:16:20,490 --> 00:16:21,490
What happens?

128
00:16:22,890 --> 00:16:25,350
We did this experiment.

129
00:16:26,050 --> 00:16:48,350
On this form, which is cardboard — you can easily get baking foil tubes, and there are also very high-quality dedicated forms.

130
00:16:48,970 --> 00:16:49,890
One option.

131
00:16:49,910 --> 00:16:54,090
Or any other cardboard tube you can find.

132
00:16:54,970 --> 00:17:05,790
We wound 30 cm on this form, with 0.75 mm wire cross-section.

133
00:17:08,130 --> 00:17:17,490
And this coil was connected to a fairly large antenna.

134
00:17:17,990 --> 00:17:26,730
The antenna is made of aluminum wire, 7 turns, winding diameter 135 mm.

135
00:17:27,910 --> 00:17:42,030
By analogy with windings on plastic tubes, I expected to see a frequency in the 600–750 kHz range.

136
00:17:42,190 --> 00:17:56,530
When the system was started and the frequency response was measured, it turned out that for such a long winding the system frequency was 1.2 MHz.

137
00:17:57,530 --> 00:18:15,610
Then on a form of the same diameter but plastic — like sewer tube — I wound the same wire and compared the frequency response.

138
00:18:16,470 --> 00:18:28,030
And to hit 1.2 MHz in the same system, I needed to wind 9.5 mm on the plastic tube.

139
00:18:29,070 --> 00:18:33,670
From which I concluded that plastic isn't at all suitable for these windings.

140
00:18:34,890 --> 00:18:38,770
Another downside of plastic tubes is this.

141
00:18:38,950 --> 00:18:43,790
It strongly suppresses both the system's frequency and its Q-factor.

142
00:18:45,230 --> 00:18:48,050
The high-voltage coil works much worse.

143
00:18:48,650 --> 00:18:57,810
You need higher supply voltage to drive the high-voltage Tesla coil specifically on a plastic tube.

144
00:18:58,570 --> 00:19:12,450
We'll see — this system as assembled is already functional from 1.6 V input.

145
00:19:12,710 --> 00:19:31,790
The self-oscillator starts up, and if we lay a probe near this antenna, you can see a clean nice sine wave already at this supply voltage.

146
00:19:31,990 --> 00:19:35,230
The Q-factor of the system is very high.

147
00:19:36,410 --> 00:19:40,290
Now, another question that comes up often.

148
00:19:41,250 --> 00:19:47,010
Can you wind these coils by soldering the wire?

149
00:19:47,870 --> 00:19:55,890
On this coil you can see 1, 2, 3, 4, and one more on this side — five solder joints.

150
00:19:56,650 --> 00:20:03,330
While dialing in the frequency, I used the wire-unwinding method.

151
00:20:04,390 --> 00:20:14,070
In the process, the wire naturally had to be cut and, to retune to other frequencies, soldered back together.

152
00:20:14,930 --> 00:20:30,350
As it turned out — if you have good grounding (in this case, very good — 25 mm² welding cable, but I also tried 4 mm² wire).

153
00:20:30,730 --> 00:20:40,070
I didn't really see any difference, so you don't have to chase welding cable to improve these systems.

154
00:20:40,230 --> 00:20:41,870
But you do want good grounding.

155
00:20:42,410 --> 00:20:59,930
And if the grounding is good, with good contact to the soil, then you won't see any operational degradation or harmonics, distortion of the sine signal, or other issues on the soldered wire.

156
00:21:00,090 --> 00:21:01,710
That is, the coil runs cleanly.

157
00:21:02,170 --> 00:21:15,130
The main thing is to clean the lacquer off both wires properly, twist them together physically, and only after that tin them with solder.

158
00:21:15,130 --> 00:21:20,850
Then put heat shrink on it, and the wire works without issues.

159
00:21:24,990 --> 00:21:28,710
Now another important point.

160
00:21:30,770 --> 00:21:45,390
Few people know that Tesla coils work — if you want to put it this way — by sensing the electromagnetic radiation from the inductor by volume.

161
00:21:46,070 --> 00:21:56,270
For the inductor's given dimensions, there's a minimum allowable geometric size for the Tesla coil itself.

162
00:21:56,970 --> 00:22:12,990
If you don't respect those minimum dimensions, the inductor will go into excitation on its own, develop its own oscillations, mess with the whole system, and the high-voltage coil will be much worse coordinated.

163
00:22:12,990 --> 00:22:19,670
With the inductor itself.

164
00:22:20,310 --> 00:22:33,690
Don't, just to lower the frequency, wind with very thin wire — that is, wires under 0.5 mm cross-section.

165
00:22:34,590 --> 00:22:42,470
On Tesla coils with tube diameters of 40 to 50 mm, you shouldn't use thin wires.

166
00:22:42,990 --> 00:22:54,230
We need a certain volume occupied by this coil in space to pick up the electromagnetic wave from the inductor.

167
00:22:55,630 --> 00:22:58,490
You need to understand and coordinate this.

168
00:22:59,170 --> 00:23:03,050
There are also two ways to dial in the frequency.

169
00:23:03,890 --> 00:23:12,130
We talked about the first — unwinding the wire — which raises the frequency.

170
00:23:12,830 --> 00:23:15,810
Or we can go the other way.

171
00:23:16,170 --> 00:23:35,210
We can leave the wire length in the system as it is — what fills the form — and change the frequency via the geometric dimensions: stretching the antenna, increasing the diameter, or increasing the number of turns.

172
00:23:35,210 --> 00:23:37,650
Of turns on the antenna itself.

173
00:23:38,410 --> 00:23:43,010
In some cases of the systems we work with, it's preferable.

174
00:23:43,090 --> 00:23:58,810
Say if we need to keep a certain wire length for the high-voltage coil to match the receiving coil's wire length, and the frequency needs to be changed — that is, tuned by frequency.

175
00:23:58,810 --> 00:24:01,650
Tuned by frequency.

176
00:24:02,250 --> 00:24:09,670
The wire length stays unchanged, and we change the frequency by adjusting the antenna.

177
00:24:10,750 --> 00:24:14,450
About the antenna — very important info.

178
00:24:16,810 --> 00:24:20,810
You can't wind the antenna out of copper wire.

179
00:24:21,610 --> 00:24:30,370
First, copper wire has a hard time parting with static charge.

180
00:24:31,370 --> 00:24:45,390
Copper is more for working with direct current movement — heavy charge moving along the surface or in the crystal lattice of the conductor.

181
00:24:45,390 --> 00:24:46,510
Of the conductor.

182
00:24:47,130 --> 00:24:52,310
That material is good for places where you need to create a magnetic field.

183
00:24:52,870 --> 00:25:00,110
Where you need to work with static, I recommend using aluminum.

184
00:25:00,550 --> 00:25:03,370
First, here's the test we did.

185
00:25:04,170 --> 00:25:12,910
We wound an antenna of aluminum, and another of copper wire with the same cross-section.

186
00:25:13,370 --> 00:25:19,630
Identical dimensions, wire length, diameter — and we measured the frequencies.

187
00:25:20,030 --> 00:25:34,030
And it turned out that with a copper antenna, the system frequency was 150 kHz lower than with an aluminum antenna of identical geometric dimensions.

188
00:25:35,270 --> 00:25:38,350
You can run these experiments yourself and confirm it.

189
00:25:39,270 --> 00:25:42,470
So I don't recommend using copper for the antenna.

190
00:25:43,170 --> 00:25:48,110
Copper creates a strong magnetic field, by the way.

191
00:25:48,350 --> 00:25:57,610
When our systems are running, we can't have a magnetic field right there in the antenna zone.

192
00:25:58,090 --> 00:26:09,750
We need an alternating electric potential that'll later interact with the magnetic field in our resonator.

193
00:26:10,270 --> 00:26:12,730
That's why we use aluminum.

194
00:26:15,270 --> 00:26:18,150
Moving on to how our device runs.

195
00:26:18,290 --> 00:26:21,570
Let's look at the supply-side oscillograms.

196
00:26:23,590 --> 00:26:28,390
We'll start this system from a lab power supply.

197
00:26:28,750 --> 00:26:36,490
The supply is at 1.3 V and the current draw is zero.

198
00:26:36,630 --> 00:26:38,830
So the system isn't running yet.

199
00:26:40,930 --> 00:26:47,790
The yellow oscilloscope channel — the probe itself — is hooked to the transistor's collector.

200
00:26:48,950 --> 00:26:57,890
The oscilloscope common is on the grounding wire, basically on the transistor's emitter and the wire going to ground.

201
00:26:59,890 --> 00:27:09,850
Now I'll smoothly raise the supply voltage and we'll see at what voltage the system starts.

202
00:27:10,210 --> 00:27:18,530
That is, we'll see sine-wave oscillations on the blue oscilloscope channel.

203
00:27:20,170 --> 00:27:21,390
Raising the voltage.

204
00:27:22,970 --> 00:27:32,890
And here we see the voltage went up by just a few tenths of a volt.

205
00:27:33,150 --> 00:27:37,850
It's now 1.3 V.

206
00:27:37,950 --> 00:27:42,610
And basically no current draw from the system.

207
00:27:42,890 --> 00:27:46,070
But the system is already running.

208
00:27:47,990 --> 00:27:55,470
That is, winding on a cardboard form gives a very high Q-factor.

209
00:27:55,570 --> 00:27:59,950
It can run on minimum consumption.

210
00:28:02,130 --> 00:28:04,190
Increasing the supply.

211
00:28:05,350 --> 00:28:06,890
Now you can clearly see it.

212
00:28:07,170 --> 00:28:09,210
1.4 V.

213
00:28:09,970 --> 00:28:11,330
1.5 V.

214
00:28:11,330 --> 00:28:13,610
1.6 V.

215
00:28:13,630 --> 00:28:14,670
1.7 V.

216
00:28:14,670 --> 00:28:16,550
1.8 V.

217
00:28:17,250 --> 00:28:35,270
At 1.8 V, current draw 0.03 A, the antenna already has potential that can be picked up with a neon bulb.

218
00:28:36,170 --> 00:28:38,870
You see the lamp lights up when you touch the wire.

219
00:28:40,090 --> 00:28:43,290
The system starts to show its properties.

220
00:28:44,050 --> 00:28:48,410
Of course we don't run it at these levels.

221
00:28:49,510 --> 00:28:51,630
Now I'll raise the supply voltage.

222
00:28:54,250 --> 00:29:00,350
And we'll look at the oscillogram of the transistor's operation directly on the collector.

223
00:29:00,470 --> 00:29:14,460
So we can see how the system runs, sync up, and analyze.

224
00:29:14,900 --> 00:29:25,420
Here we see the peaks I was talking about — high-frequency, on the collector.

225
00:29:27,320 --> 00:29:37,220
You see the sync — the transistor fires on the positive half-period of the coil's own oscillation.

226
00:29:39,300 --> 00:29:51,260
The system's operating frequency — you can see in the upper-right corner — is 1.33 MHz.

227
00:29:52,780 --> 00:30:02,640
The winding is now 4.5 cm on the coil form.

228
00:30:03,320 --> 00:30:08,140
Form diameter is 25 cm of winding.

229
00:30:08,840 --> 00:30:15,400
At such an antenna, you can see the frequency is pretty high.

230
00:30:16,420 --> 00:30:21,800
And we see our transistor starts working.

231
00:30:22,080 --> 00:30:31,080
First spike, then voltage drop, then another spike, then another.

232
00:30:31,440 --> 00:30:34,100
Now I'll raise the supply voltage too.

233
00:30:34,100 --> 00:30:36,260
Now it's 7.5 V.

234
00:30:36,480 --> 00:30:40,300
And we'll see the number of spikes go up.

235
00:30:40,960 --> 00:30:43,420
But with that, the amplitude grows.

236
00:30:44,480 --> 00:30:46,020
Bringing it to nominal.

237
00:30:46,900 --> 00:30:48,020
Now 9 V.

238
00:30:49,880 --> 00:30:57,020
And look at the spike amplitude when supply is at 24 V.

239
00:31:02,840 --> 00:31:06,760
Now precisely set at 24 V supply.

240
00:31:07,400 --> 00:31:12,760
You can see another peak appeared.

241
00:31:13,860 --> 00:31:22,100
So, raising the supply amplitude, the number of spikes goes up.

242
00:31:22,940 --> 00:31:31,560
And the more spikes there are, the better our system works — more economical.

243
00:31:31,840 --> 00:31:36,000
Compared to tuning the system to have only one peak.

244
00:31:36,600 --> 00:31:42,760
In this case you can see the spike amplitude.

245
00:31:43,940 --> 00:31:51,080
The highest amplitude on the first pulse is 136 V.

246
00:31:51,080 --> 00:31:54,260
At 24 V supply.

247
00:31:55,240 --> 00:32:03,920
And we see the voltage matches the 24 V applied to the input.

248
00:32:04,760 --> 00:32:11,000
And consumption is just 0.6 A.

249
00:32:11,640 --> 00:32:21,240
You'll also notice the lamp near the antenna lights up.

250
00:32:21,920 --> 00:32:25,380
The fluorescent lights up brightly, really well.

251
00:32:26,460 --> 00:32:32,840
All the effects you'd expect in normal mode operation, we have them.

252
00:32:33,500 --> 00:32:37,600
The neon bulb glows at a big distance.

253
00:32:37,700 --> 00:32:39,540
Let's check the distance.

254
00:32:39,840 --> 00:32:45,620
Starts glowing about 35 cm from the antenna.

255
00:32:47,920 --> 00:32:54,900
There's also a stable discharge onto metal objects.

256
00:32:56,680 --> 00:32:58,220
Let's look at it now.

257
00:33:03,440 --> 00:33:10,020
About a centimeter long.

258
00:33:15,120 --> 00:33:17,840
You can stretch a stable arc.

259
00:33:21,490 --> 00:33:26,570
So all the accompanying effects show up with this tuning.

260
00:33:27,670 --> 00:33:35,310
It works no worse than when we have a single spike, but in a much more economical mode.

261
00:33:36,230 --> 00:33:39,050
I recommend exactly this mode on the Kacher.

262
00:33:39,690 --> 00:33:40,730
You'll see the difference.

263
00:33:42,330 --> 00:33:44,650
It's clearly noticeable.

264
00:33:48,190 --> 00:34:00,930
You can also verify another interesting feature if we sync the oscilloscope not on the grounding wire but on the positive supply.

265
00:34:01,150 --> 00:34:03,710
The sync was on grounding before.

266
00:34:03,930 --> 00:34:11,430
Now we'll clamp onto the plus supply and look at what's on the collector.

267
00:34:12,850 --> 00:34:24,190
Hooked the common to plus, clipped onto the heat sink lug, since it's not galvanically connected to the collector.

268
00:34:26,370 --> 00:34:33,050
And now we examine the operation with this measurement.

269
00:34:37,650 --> 00:34:39,170
Raising the voltage.

270
00:34:42,110 --> 00:34:49,310
Now 19, 20, 24 V supply.

271
00:34:50,850 --> 00:34:56,910
What's interesting to note in this mode?

272
00:34:56,990 --> 00:35:17,130
Since we're synced relative to plus supply, the maximum amplitude is lower, 106 V, but we can also see the drop amplitude in the minus common, which —

273
00:35:17,130 --> 00:35:24,230
since we're synced on plus — corresponds roughly to the supply voltage.

274
00:35:25,170 --> 00:35:31,430
Now 24 V, but we read about 27 V drop here.

275
00:35:31,550 --> 00:35:44,350
There's some shift toward minus visible, but the peaks are positive — even relative to the system's plus supply.

276
00:35:47,190 --> 00:36:03,120
Nothing mysterious here — because the spike amplitude itself has positive potential much greater than the potential of the supply applied to plus input.

277
00:36:03,380 --> 00:36:09,280
So relative to plus we see the drop, basically equal to the supply voltage.

278
00:36:10,120 --> 00:36:15,320
And the pulse itself goes to the positive half-period.

279
00:36:16,640 --> 00:36:33,460
The marker labeled "1" — the yellow one — shows the start of zero on the scale, the one the oscillogram is centered on.

280
00:36:36,630 --> 00:36:55,130
You can also measure on the transistor's base — without fear of frying the oscilloscope — when the system is connected to grounding.

281
00:36:55,530 --> 00:37:01,190
Nothing scary, the oscillogram can be observed there.

282
00:37:01,330 --> 00:37:15,090
Now I'll connect a second oscilloscope probe directly to the base and look at the signal coming from the coil to this transistor's base.

283
00:37:16,610 --> 00:37:21,790
Hooked the second oscilloscope channel directly to the transistor base.

284
00:37:22,070 --> 00:37:29,190
You can see it's at the midpoint of the resistor divider.

285
00:37:30,070 --> 00:37:34,090
That is, connected here.

286
00:37:35,330 --> 00:37:40,390
Actually connected to the cold end of the high-voltage coil.

287
00:37:41,110 --> 00:37:54,970
You can make measurements like this with the oscilloscope at this point, provided you have good grounding for the high-voltage coil.

288
00:37:56,470 --> 00:38:05,370
If you have doubts about your grounding, you need to set up here, look at something.

289
00:38:05,890 --> 00:38:09,830
You need the device — the oscilloscope itself — to not be grounded.

290
00:38:10,910 --> 00:38:12,870
This is important for the work.

291
00:38:13,610 --> 00:38:18,750
I also recommend it for how you power the device.

292
00:38:19,170 --> 00:38:25,090
These are usually pretty expensive for us, and we don't want to part with them.

293
00:38:25,650 --> 00:38:32,590
You want the device's power supply isolated from grounding.

294
00:38:33,490 --> 00:38:40,970
On the device's plug you can always see the grounding contact.

295
00:38:41,310 --> 00:38:47,230
It shouldn't be connected to grounding when working with the high-voltage coil.

296
00:38:47,750 --> 00:38:48,110
That's one.

297
00:38:48,350 --> 00:38:49,130
And one more.

298
00:38:50,210 --> 00:38:59,230
Oscilloscope devices, signal generators, and so on — better to power them through two transformers, for example.

299
00:38:59,350 --> 00:39:12,050
Say you have two transformers, around 200–300 W each, enough to power several devices.

300
00:39:12,230 --> 00:39:13,930
Or at least the oscilloscope.

301
00:39:14,450 --> 00:39:22,530
You connect it first through a winding for mains 220 V.

302
00:39:22,610 --> 00:39:28,010
Then in step-down mode it outputs, say, 12, 24, or 36 V.

303
00:39:28,650 --> 00:39:31,270
And the second identical one is connected in reverse.

304
00:39:32,050 --> 00:39:34,450
With, say, a 12 V winding.

305
00:39:34,450 --> 00:39:44,210
From the 12 V output of the first transformer you get the output voltage that goes to the device's mains winding.

306
00:39:45,570 --> 00:39:50,770
That's how you isolate the device through two transformers from the mains.

307
00:39:51,550 --> 00:39:54,870
Very useful in the work and it protects your gear.

308
00:39:55,510 --> 00:40:00,170
And we can see the oscillogram on the transistor's base.

309
00:40:00,830 --> 00:40:02,070
This is by voltage.

310
00:40:02,490 --> 00:40:03,470
Here's the oscillogram.

311
00:40:04,610 --> 00:40:14,270
You see the transistor on the collector copies the voltage shape on the base.

312
00:40:15,950 --> 00:40:23,030
These signals we have, exactly on the positive half-period.

313
00:40:23,970 --> 00:40:26,550
This is just for interest.

314
00:40:26,610 --> 00:40:31,050
If you're curious, you can look for yourself and investigate.

315
00:40:32,270 --> 00:40:41,190
And we can also do, say, a measurement in this system through a current sensor.

316
00:40:41,930 --> 00:40:50,930
Let's look — with a sensor made on a ferrite ring — what happens in the grounding wire.

317
00:40:51,070 --> 00:40:54,250
We can examine it by current.

318
00:40:54,430 --> 00:40:57,150
Now I'll install the sensor and we'll look.

319
00:40:59,590 --> 00:41:01,990
Current sensor connected.

320
00:41:02,430 --> 00:41:08,930
It goes directly on the wire going from the transistor emitter to grounding.

321
00:41:11,250 --> 00:41:19,710
And the second oscilloscope channel is about 15 cm from the antenna.

322
00:41:20,250 --> 00:41:23,310
Another important note on device protection.

323
00:41:23,690 --> 00:41:36,570
Never connect the oscilloscope to the high-voltage end of the coil, or to its termination — which is this antenna.

324
00:41:37,650 --> 00:41:40,870
You can easily lose your device.

325
00:41:40,970 --> 00:41:52,430
All voltage measurements in this case are done with the probe at some distance from the high-voltage part.

326
00:41:53,450 --> 00:42:00,450
I use probes — I recommend these — rated for 1500 V.

327
00:42:00,710 --> 00:42:10,070
They handle frequencies and voltages really well, even with ordinary electronics.

328
00:42:10,250 --> 00:42:15,270
I specifically bought them — they don't come in the oscilloscope kit.

329
00:42:15,570 --> 00:42:23,050
But 1500 V gives you a nice reserve so you don't fry your device.

330
00:42:24,710 --> 00:42:28,250
And now we hooked up the current sensor and we examine the oscillogram.

331
00:42:29,730 --> 00:42:37,370
Reminder — yellow channel is current in the grounding wire, blue is voltage.

332
00:42:37,950 --> 00:42:45,870
We see we have a phase shift between current — yellow channel — and voltage.

333
00:42:46,270 --> 00:42:49,650
And you can see these characteristic signals by current.

334
00:42:49,870 --> 00:42:53,230
Remember this signal —

335
00:42:55,230 --> 00:43:01,110
those peak strikes show up specifically by current.

336
00:43:01,150 --> 00:43:04,030
Those points above the sine wave.

337
00:43:04,930 --> 00:43:15,350
And the correct polarity for the current sensor on this system is when current leads voltage.

338
00:43:15,430 --> 00:43:17,090
Voltage is now the blue channel.

339
00:43:17,090 --> 00:43:27,550
We don't see a clean 90-degree phase shift right now — to see that precisely, you'd need to hang a resistor on the current sensor.

340
00:43:28,190 --> 00:43:41,450
But nevertheless, there really is a 90-degree shift in our high-voltage coil, because all the processes for us happen by current in these systems.

341
00:43:42,410 --> 00:43:43,370
Why by current?

342
00:43:43,470 --> 00:43:55,730
Because to start it, the whole process kicks off when the transistor switches the voltage applied to it, which feeds current into the inductor.

343
00:43:56,330 --> 00:43:58,490
The inductor creates a magnetic field.

344
00:43:59,030 --> 00:44:02,290
The magnetic field strikes the coil.

345
00:44:02,430 --> 00:44:07,330
Current passed through the inductor, created a magnetic field.

346
00:44:07,490 --> 00:44:15,230
The magnetic field acts on the coil, after which oscillations ramp up in it.

347
00:44:15,350 --> 00:44:19,510
So voltage lags relative to current.

348
00:44:21,110 --> 00:44:30,210
And the correct polarity is when the oscillogram shows current leading voltage.

349
00:44:33,330 --> 00:44:35,330
Good luck to everyone with your experiments.

350
00:44:35,510 --> 00:44:58,030
In subsequent videos we'll look at how this assembled circuit will help us determine the frequency the high-voltage, high-frequency part should run at relative to our grenade.
